snippet.textDisplay: Wow! - Amazing space. There's a general myth that adding foam panels to the walls is "sound proofing". This is acoustic treatment, meant to deaden the room so there is less reverb. Soundproofing is a completely different thing, that is intended to stop sounds getting out (or in) the room - usually for loud sources such as drums. Soundproofing will do nothing to deaden the echo in the room. Please don't confuse the two!!
snippet.textOriginal: Wow! - Amazing space. There's a general myth that adding foam panels to the walls is "sound proofing". This is acoustic treatment, meant to deaden the room so there is less reverb. Soundproofing is a completely different thing, that is intended to stop sounds getting out (or in) the room - usually for loud sources such as drums. snippet.textDisplay:
I am happy for you Marques! For me, the main parameter of a studio is to have all power coming from the ceeling. There should be no cables on the floor to ensure work safety. Also some modular/flexible rail system on the ceeling to hang heavy equipment and lighting on it is essential to utilize the space in the most efficient way. A simple rail in the shape # will work well, if you can move it throughout the whole lenght of your studio space!


All the Best to you and your team :)
